Would you Trade a Chocolate for An Apple?

Draft – 31 Nov 2025
Authors: Mateo, Erik, Thomas, Siramane, Chen, Eriya

Do trade policies influence your choice of snack?

Several economies around the world are adopting a more proactive public health policy to improve nutrition and reduce non-communicable diseases, such as coronary heart disease, stroke and diabetes. As public health agencies and researchers increasingly focus on whether the processing of foods (e.g. additives, preservatives, and flavourings) negatively affects health, this note examines data on international food trade (specifically, trade flows and tariffs) to understand the linkages between trade policies and the type of food traded across borders.

Two caveats are important :

  1. We do not suggest that trade policy is an instrument for health policy. This blog is agnostic on the policy choice of WTO Members – it is solely intended to highlight the existence of possible patterns among policy choices through an analysis of data (HS lines and tariffs).

  2. Nothing here should be taken to suggest that all food processing necessarily poses a risk to human health or negatively impacts the nutritional quality of food. Processing technologies, like pasteurization and refrigeration, have played essential roles in ensuring food safety, nutritional quality, and accessibility.

From tariff lines to food processing categories

This note contributes to the growing body of work linking trade and nutrition by systematically identifying relevant food products at the tariff-line level under the Harmonized System (HS) and mapping them to the NOVA classification, which categorizes foods by degree of processing. This approach enables a direct connection between international trade data and the degree of food processing, enabling a closer examination of trade and nutrition linkages.

The NOVA food classification system categorizes foods into four groups according to their degree of processing. For analytical clarity, we group them in three clusters:

  • Unprocessed foods (NOVA 1) – ~60% of our basket (e.g. fresh fruits/vegetables, grains, legumes).
  • Processed foods (NOVA 2–3) – ~32% of our basket (e.g. oils, sugar, salt, canned vegetables, cheese, bread).
  • Ultra-processed foods (NOVA 4) – ~8% of our basket (e.g. ice-cream, sugary drinks, packaged snacks, instant noodles).

In total, we apply this classification to 797 HS6 lines covering most traded food products.

What the Data Reveal :

From 1996 to 2024, global imports of unprocessed foods have grown more rapidly than those of processed or ultra-processed foods, both in total value and on a per capita basis. The increase in total value has been most pronounced in Asia, while per capita imports rose strongly in Europe, North America, and Oceania. In contrast, imports of processed and ultra-processed foods increased modestly or stabilized.

Average MFN tariffs tend to be lower for unprocessed foods than for processed or ultra-processed foods—but not everywhere. Among top importers, some economies impose higher tariffs on ultra-processed vs. unprocessed foods (e.g. Canada, Russian Federation, Japan), while others (e.g. Türkiye, India, Korea) apply higher tariffs on unprocessed products.

Linking trade and nutrition: takeaways and next steps

Mapping tariffs onto NOVA provides a useful lens on how trade policies and nutrition may intersect. Although MFN tariffs often favour unprocessed foods, there is no single global pattern. Meanwhile, trade in food overall has grown, with unprocessed imports expanding faster than processed and ultra-processed products.

Beyond tariffs, non-tariff measures (e.g. nutrition labels, advertising restrictions, reformulation standards) shape consumption. Many food-related regulations are notified to the WTO under the TBT Agreement, with several raised as Specific Trade Concerns. A future instalment will examine these measures in more detail.
